body:
I described this problem on this [StackOverflow question](https://stackoverflow.com/q/69535907/124486). I'm migrating from using `Vec<&str>` to the more generic `&[&str]` on the suggestion of internet peoples. And, I encountered a really horrible diagnostic which sent me down the rabbit hole,

This works fine,

```rust
fn main() { 
  let pos: Vec<String> = vec!["foo".to_owned(), "bar".to_owned(), "baz".to_owned()];
  let pos: Vec<&str> = pos.iter().map(AsRef::as_ref).collect(); 
}
```

However, this raises all kinds of problems,

```rust
fn main() { 
  let pos: Vec<String> = vec!["foo".to_owned(), "bar".to_owned(), "baz".to_owned()];
  let pos: &[&str] = pos.iter().map(AsRef::as_ref).collect(); 
}
```

You can see the invitation to go down the rabbit hole here,

```text
error[E0277]: a value of type `&[&str]` cannot be built from an iterator over elements of type `&_`
 --> bin/seq.rs:3:51
  |
  |     let pos: &[&str] = pos.iter().map(AsRef::as_ref).collect(); 
  |                                                      ^^^^^^^ value of type `&[&str]` cannot be built from `std::iter::Iterator<Item=&_>`
  |
  = help: the trait `FromIterator<&_>` is not implemented for `&[&str]`

For more information about this error, try `rustc --explain E0277`.
```

So in order to solve

> value of type `&[&str]` cannot be built from `std::iter::Iterator<Item=&_>

You need to simply add `.to_slice()`,

```rust
  let pos: Vec<String> = vec!["foo".to_owned(), "bar".to_owned(), "baz".to_owned()];
  let pos: Vec<&str> = pos.iter().map(AsRef::as_ref).collect();
  let pos: &[&str] = pos.as_slice();
```

Or alternatively

```rust
let pos: &[&str] = pos.iter().map(AsRef::as_ref).collect::<Vec<_>>().as_slice();
```
